It also is used for a debt, and ‘nomen solvere’ is to pay a debt;

‘ nomen facere,’ either to incur a debt or to lend money; for ‘ facere' is used in both senses: but ‘ nomen' is also used for the debtor himself, as in Cicero (ad Fam. v. 6. 2), “Meis rebus gestis hoc sum assecutus ut bonum nomen existimer.'’ Porphyrion explains ‘nominibus rectis ' as ‘ de legibus factis non de foenerando debitoribus.'
